{"schema":"algviz/1","title":"Merge K Sorted Lists (min-heap)","topic":"linked-lists","code":["public ListNode MergeKLists(ListNode[] lists)","{","    var pq = new PriorityQueue<ListNode, int>();","    foreach (ListNode node in lists)","        if (node != null) pq.Enqueue(node, node.val);","    var dummy = new ListNode();","    ListNode tail = dummy;","    while (pq.Count > 0)","    {","        ListNode smallest = pq.Dequeue();","        tail.next = smallest;","        tail = tail.next;","        if (smallest.next != null)","            pq.Enqueue(smallest.next, smallest.next.val);","    }","    return dummy.next;","}"],"structures":{"lists":{"type":"graph","label":"k sorted lists (one row each)"},"heap":{"type":"array1d","label":"min-heap: one head per live list (size <= k)"},"merged":{"type":"queue","label":"merged list (dummy -> tail)"}},"frames":[{"line":5,"caption":"Push the head of every list into a min-heap keyed by value. The heap now holds the k frontier nodes: values 1, 1, 2.","note":"Brute force concatenates and sorts (O(N log N)) or merges lists one at a time (O(N*k)). The heap insight: at any moment the next-smallest node in the whole answer is the minimum of just the k current heads. A min-heap peeks that minimum in O(1) and updates in O(log k), so we never re-examine a node we have passed.","vars":{"k":3,"heap":"[1, 1, 2]"},"result":null,"states":{"lists":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"l0n0","value":1,"x":16,"y":18,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"l0n1","value":4,"x":38,"y":18},{"key":"l0n2","value":5,"x":60,"y":18},{"key":"l1n0","value":1,"x":16,"y":50,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"l1n1","value":3,"x":38,"y":50},{"key":"l1n2","value":4,"x":60,"y":50},{"key":"l2n0","value":2,"x":16,"y":82,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"l2n1","value":6,"x":38,"y":82}],"edges":[{"from":"l0n0","to":"l0n1"},{"from":"l0n1","to":"l0n2"},{"from":"l1n0","to":"l1n1"},{"from":"l1n1","to":"l1n2"},{"from":"l2n0","to":"l2n1"}]},"heap":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"cl0n0","value":1},{"key":"cl1n0","value":1},{"key":"cl2n0","value":2}],"range":null},"merged":{"type":"queue","items":[],"front":0}}},{"line":10,"caption":"Pop the global minimum: 1 (from list 0). It is the next node in the merged order.","note":"Dequeue returns the GLOBAL minimum across all k lists in O(log k), because the heap holds exactly one frontier node per still-alive list — the current head of each. That node must be the next value in the fully merged order: every list is sorted, so nothing behind a list head can beat it, and the heap already compared the k heads against each other.","vars":{"k":3,"heap":"[1, 1, 2]","smallest":1,"heapSize":2},"result":null,"states":{"lists":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"l0n0","value":1,"x":16,"y":18,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"l0n1","value":4,"x":38,"y":18},{"key":"l0n2","value":5,"x":60,"y":18},{"key":"l1n0","value":1,"x":16,"y":50,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"l1n1","value":3,"x":38,"y":50},{"key":"l1n2","value":4,"x":60,"y":50},{"key":"l2n0","value":2,"x":16,"y":82,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"l2n1","value":6,"x":38,"y":82}],"edges":[{"from":"l0n0","to":"l0n1"},{"from":"l0n1","to":"l0n2"},{"from":"l1n0","to":"l1n1"},{"from":"l1n1","to":"l1n2"},{"from":"l2n0","to":"l2n1"}]},"heap":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"cl1n0","value":1},{"key":"cl2n0","value":2}],"range":null},"merged":{"type":"queue","items":[],"front":0}}},{"line":12,"caption":"Append 1 to the merged list's tail. Merged so far: 1.","note":"tail.next = smallest then tail = tail.next splices the popped node onto the end in O(1). A dummy head means the very first append is the same code as every other — no special case for an empty result list.","vars":{"k":3,"heap":"[1, 1, 2]","smallest":1,"heapSize":2,"merged":"[1]"},"result":null,"states":{"lists":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"l0n0","value":1,"x":16,"y":18,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"l0n1","value":4,"x":38,"y":18},{"key":"l0n2","value":5,"x":60,"y":18},{"key":"l1n0","value":1,"x":16,"y":50,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"l1n1","value":3,"x":38,"y":50},{"key":"l1n2","value":4,"x":60,"y":50},{"key":"l2n0","value":2,"x":16,"y":82,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"l2n1","value":6,"x":38,"y":82}],"edges":[{"from":"l0n0","to":"l0n1"},{"from":"l0n1","to":"l0n2"},{"from":"l1n0","to":"l1n1"},{"from":"l1n1","to":"l1n2"},{"from":"l2n0","to":"l2n1"}]},"heap":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"cl1n0","value":1},{"key":"cl2n0","value":2}],"range":null},"merged":{"type":"queue","items":[{"key":"q0","value":1,"highlight":"match"}],"front":0}}},{"line":14,"caption":"That list advances: push 0's next node (4) so the heap keeps one head per live list.","note":"After taking a node, its list advances by one: push that node.next so the list keeps exactly one candidate in the heap. The heap therefore stays at size <= k forever — that bound is the whole trick. N total pops, each pop+push O(log k), gives O(N log k). Contrast the trap: merging lists one-at-a-time into an accumulator re-walks earlier nodes and costs O(N*k).","vars":{"k":3,"heap":"[1, 2, 4]","smallest":1,"heapSize":2,"merged":"[1]"},"result":null,"states":{"lists":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"l0n0","value":1,"x":16,"y":18,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"l0n1","value":4,"x":38,"y":18,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"l0n2","value":5,"x":60,"y":18},{"key":"l1n0","value":1,"x":16,"y":50,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"l1n1","value":3,"x":38,"y":50},{"key":"l1n2","value":4,"x":60,"y":50},{"key":"l2n0","value":2,"x":16,"y":82,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"l2n1","value":6,"x":38,"y":82}],"edges":[{"from":"l0n0","to":"l0n1"},{"from":"l0n1","to":"l0n2"},{"from":"l1n0","to":"l1n1"},{"from":"l1n1","to":"l1n2"},{"from":"l2n0","to":"l2n1"}]},"heap":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"cl1n0","value":1},{"key":"cl2n0","value":2},{"key":"cl0n1","value":4,"highlight":"active"}],"range":null},"merged":{"type":"queue","items":[{"key":"q0","value":1,"highlight":"match"}],"fr